  "text": "# LibreOffice Calc Formula Evaluation Chain\n\n## Overview\nThe formula evaluation in LibreOffice Calc follows a four-stage pipeline: parsing → cell scheduling → interpreter initialization → bytecode execution.\n\n## Key Files and Components\n\n### 1. Formula Compiler/Tokenizer\n**File**: `sc/source/core/tool/compiler.cxx`\n**Class**: `ScCompiler` (defined in `sc/inc/compiler.hxx:181`)\n**Key Method**: `ScCompiler::CompileString` (line 4833)\n\nThe compiler parses a formula string like `=SUM(A1:A10)` and converts it into a `ScTokenArray` (token array). The process:\n1. Strips whitespace from formula\n2. Detects formula prefix (=, ==)\n3. Tokenizes the formula text character by character\n4. Creates tokens for operators, functions, references, literals\n5. Returns a `std::unique_ptr<ScTokenArray>` containing the compiled bytecode\n\n### 2. Formula Cell Container\n**Header File**: `sc/inc/formulacell.hxx` \n**Implementation**: `sc/source/core/data/formulacell.cxx`\n**Class**: `ScFormulaCell` (line 120 in header)\n\nThis is the cell type that holds a formula. Key members:\n- `pCode` - pointer to the ScTokenArray (compiled formula bytecode)\n- `aResult` - the calculated result\n- `bDirty` - flag indicating cell needs recalculation\n- `mxGroup` - reference to formula group for grouped calculations\n\nKey methods:\n- `Interpret(SCROW nStartOffset, SCROW nEndOffset)` (line 1500) - Entry point for calculation\n  - Checks recursion and cycle detection\n  - Handles formula groups for parallel evaluation\n  - Schedules interpretation based on dirty flag\n  \n- `InterpretTail(ScInterpreterContext& rContext, ScInterpretTailParameter eTailParam)` (line 1885) - Actually invokes the interpreter\n  - Ensures token array is compiled (calls `CompileTokenArray()`)\n  - Creates or reuses a `ScInterpreter` instance\n  - Calls `pInterpreter->Interpret()` to execute the formula\n  - Handles result error codes and recalculation modes\n\n### 3. Formula Interpreter/Evaluator\n**Header File**: `sc/source/core/inc/interpre.hxx`\n**Implementation**: `sc/source/core/tool/interpr1.cxx`, `interpr2.cxx`, `interpr4.cxx`, etc.\n**Class**: `ScInterpreter` (line 197 in header)\n\nThe bytecode interpreter that evaluates the compiled formula. Key members:\n- `aCode` - FormulaTokenIterator for traversing the token array\n- `aPos` - current cell address\n- `pArr` - pointer to the token array\n- `mrContext` - ScInterpreterContext for formula evaluation state\n\nKey method:\n- `ScInterpreter::Interpret()` (line 3976 in `interpr4.cxx`) - Main interpreter loop\n  - Initializes evaluation state (error code, stack, format type)\n  - Iterates through all tokens in the formula bytecode\n  - For each token:\n    - Gets the operation code (ocPlus, ocMinus, ocSUM, etc.)\n    - Dispatches to appropriate function handler\n    - Pushes/pops operands on evaluation stack\n  - Returns final result as `StackVar` (number, string, or error)\n\nThe interpreter contains numerous function implementations:\n- Arithmetic: ScAdd, ScSubtract, ScMultiply, ScDivide\n- Statistical: ScSum, ScCount, ScAverage, ScMin, ScMax\n- Date/Time: ScGetActDate, ScGetActTime\n- Lookup: ScVLookup, ScHLookup, ScMatch, ScIndex\n- Array operations: Matrix and array formula support\n\n### 4. Recalculation Mode Management\n**Enum**: `ScRecalcMode` (line 59 in `include/formula/tokenarray.hxx`)\n\nDefines WHEN a formula cell should be recalculated:\n- `ALWAYS` - recalculate on every change (highest priority)\n- `ONLOAD_MUST` - always recalculate after document load\n- `ONLOAD_ONCE` - recalculate once after load (import filters)\n- `ONLOAD_LENIENT` - recalculate after load if dependencies allow\n- `NORMAL` - standard recalculation on cell/reference changes\n- `FORCED` - forced recalculation even if not visible (macros)\n- `ONREFMOVE` - recalculate if references move\n\n**Key Method**: `FormulaTokenArray::AddRecalcMode` (line 945 in `formula/source/core/api/token.cxx`)\n\nThis method sets the recalculation mode on a formula token array. It:\n1. Checks for exclusive bits (only one can be set)\n2. Marks cell dirty if recalc mode is not NORMAL\n3. Stores the mode in the token array for use by recalculation scheduler\n\n## Evaluation Flow Example: =SUM(A1:A10)\n\n1. **Parsing** (`ScCompiler::CompileString`)\n   - Input: \"=SUM(A1:A10)\"\n   - Output: Token array with: [SUM, RANGE(A1:A10)]\n   - Sets recalc mode (typically NORMAL)\n\n2. **Cell Scheduling** (`ScFormulaCell::Interpret`)\n   - Checks if cell is dirty (bDirty flag)\n   - Verifies no circular references\n   - Handles formula groups for parallel evaluation\n   - Calls `InterpretTail` for actual evaluation\n\n3. **Interpreter Setup** (`ScFormulaCell::InterpretTail`)\n   - Ensures formula is compiled (CompileTokenArray)\n   - Creates ScInterpreter with:\n     - Formula cell pointer (this)\n     - Document reference\n     - Interpreter context\n     - Cell address\n     - Token array\n   - Calls `pInterpreter->Interpret()`\n\n4. **Bytecode Execution** (`ScInterpreter::Interpret`)\n   - Processes tokens sequentially\n   - For SUM token:\n     - Calls `ScSum()` function\n     - Pops range argument A1:A10 from stack\n     - Iterates cells in range, accumulating values\n     - Pushes result back on stack\n   - Returns result to cell\n\n5. **Result Storage**\n   - Result stored in `ScFormulaCell::aResult`\n   - Format type determined (number, text, error)\n   - Cell marked clean (bDirty = false)\n   - Dependents notified for recalculation\n\n## Architecture Notes\n\n- **Two-phase compilation**: Formulas are compiled once by `ScCompiler`, then interpreted multiple times by `ScInterpreter`\n- **Interpreter context**: `ScInterpreterContext` maintains shared state (document, formatter, number pool) for interpreter instances\n- **Formula groups**: Multiple contiguous formula cells with identical formulas can be evaluated together for performance\n- **Error handling**: Errors propagate through the token stack and are stored in the result\n- **Recalculation scheduling**: The `ScRecalcMode` determines when the document scheduler will mark cells dirty and request recalculation\n- **Recursion protection**: Circular references are detected and limited to prevent infinite loops\n"
}

